91.     You can now make sub groups in your configurations! These can be 
        loaded only from the list of configurations. You can create identic  
        configurations in different sub groups, AUTOCONF will of course make 
        the difference!

        To make a sub configuration, just add another start to the 
        DEVICE=* line in CONFIG.SYS.

        So,   DEVICE=*A Config A
              DEVICE=**B Config B

        means that in the main group, you will have a configuration A, in the
        list, a small arrow will be printed, meaning you have a sub group   
        under this configuration (that can still be loaded normally). By   
        pressing the right arrow a list will be sown, that is the sub group, 
        containing the B configuration. This is valid for any sub config
        of any depth! You can of course go back to the previous list by
        pressing the left arrow (not like in MS-DOS multiconf).

        Choose the configuration as usual!             

   Note: the parameter /D or /H will not (yet) accept sub configurations.
   Note: the /S parameter will perfectly work.

92.     READCONF will create a new variable CONF for sub configurations.

        ex: for the configuration A, it will still be "A", but for the 
        config B in the sub group of A, it will be "A_B".

        so (for those who didn't get it yet):

        config:                 variable CONF:
        ---------------------------------------
        F2-                     F2
           F1                   F2_F1
           F2-                  F2_F2
              F                 F2_F2_F
              G                 F2_F2_G
              H                 F2_F2_H
           F3-                  F2_F3
              J-                F2_F3_J
                O               F2_F3_J_O
        C                       C
        ---------------------------------------

  Note: the structure of AUTOCONF.DAT has been modified! The file is now  
  normally 43 bytes.

